      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of brisk walking to warm up the foot and get blood flowing before any running. This is non-negotiable — the plantar fascia needs gentle loading before impact.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easiest conversational pace (5:58/km). If you feel any foot discomfort at any point, drop to a walk immediately — no pushing through. Aim for 2–3 minutes running, 1 minute walking if needed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 3 minutes. After stopping, do a gentle calf stretch and plantar fascia stretch (toe extension against a wall) for 30 seconds each side.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes of brisk walking before any running. Gentle ankle circles and calf raises (5 each) are a good addition if your physio has cleared those movements.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes, then stretch calves and plantar fascia gently. Ice the foot for 10–15 minutes if there is any residual soreness — this is a smart recovery tool, not a sign of failure.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, you've been building really consistently over the past two weeks — three runs completed, distances creeping up, and your most recent run hit 3.4 km with no reported pain. That's meaningful progress. This Monday run keeps the same 20-minute cap your physio set, but we're nudging the target distance very slightly to reflect your recent form. The goal here is simple: accumulate easy aerobic time, keep the foot happy, and build the habit of three days per week. Pace is 5:58/km — the slow end of your easy range — and that's intentional. Your cardiovascular fitness from your 44:00 10K is still in there; we're not rebuilding your engine, we're rebuilding the chassis. Walk breaks are always available and always smart.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Foot Check-In\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Pay attention to how the foot feels during the walk — this is your early warning system. If there is any sharp or stabbing sensation during the warmup walk, today becomes a full rest day.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational running at 5:58/km. Check in with the foot every 5 minutes — a quick mental scan. Mild tightness that eases as you warm up is normal; sharp or worsening pain is a stop signal.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Plantar fascia stretch and calf stretch post-run. Consider a frozen water bottle roll under the foot for 5 minutes if any tightness remains.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute walk. Do a quick foot assessment — rate your discomfort 0–10 before you start running. If it's above a 3, walk the whole session today and that's a completely valid training day.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk cooldown, calf and plantar fascia stretching. Frozen water bottle roll is a great tool here if the foot is talking to you.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday sits 48 hours after Monday, which gives the foot adequate recovery time while keeping the aerobic stimulus consistent. This is your midweek check-in run — same structure, same pace, same cap. One thing worth noting: the fact that your March 17th run came back with 'no foot pain' is a genuinely good sign. We're not taking that for granted, but it tells us the tissue is responding well to the current load. If Wednesday feels great, resist the urge to go longer or faster — that's the hardest discipline in return-to-run, and it's also the most important one.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Easy Long Run — Aerobic Base Builder\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes before starting. Saturday mornings can mean a stiffer foot — plantar fasciitis is often worst with the first steps of the day. Give it extra time to loosen up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running at 5:58/km. This is your 'long run' in the context of return-to-run — the label matters psychologically even if the duration matches your other runs right now. Walk breaks freely available. Focus on relaxed form: soft knees, short ground contact, no heel striking.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes. This is a good day for a slightly longer post-run stretch routine — calves, hip flexors, and plantar fascia. You have the weekend ahead to recover fully.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Longer warmup walk today — 3 to 5 minutes. If the foot feels stiff from sleep, do some gentle toe curls and calf raises before heading out. Morning plantar fasciitis stiffness typically eases within the first 5–10 minutes of movement.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes. Full lower leg stretch routine: calves (straight and bent knee), plantar fascia toe extension, and hip flexors. Ice if needed. Rest Sunday — that's an active recovery investment, not a day off.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your designated long run day, and we're honoring that structure even while the duration is capped at 20 minutes. Here's the physiological rationale: consistency of schedule builds habit and routine, which is one of the most underrated factors in return-to-run success. Right now, 'long run' means the same duration as your other runs — and that's completely appropriate. As your physio clears you for more time on feet, Saturday will be the first day we extend. Think of this week's total of roughly 10–12 km across three runs as a solid, conservative foundation. Your pre-injury weekly volume was likely much higher, but the tissue needs to earn its way back. You're doing exactly the right thing by being patient here.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
